\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces PGOB-vs-baseline improved-observable counts, partitioned by baseline type and \emph  {not} summed across groups. The \textbf  {capability} group's baseline is an Initialized (deliberately randomised) parameter set, so the comparison measures whether PGOB regenerates a working simulator; the \textbf  {deployment} group's baseline is the simulator's expert-calibrated shipped default, so the comparison measures whether PGOB still adds value on top of a well-tuned default. Because an Initialized-start and an expert-default improved-count answer different questions, they are reported side by side but never aggregated into a single number. Counts are per-observable improved fractions (PGOB closer to the real reference than the baseline).}}{16}{table.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:parity_groups}{{5}{16}{PGOB-vs-baseline improved-observable counts, partitioned by baseline type and \emph {not} summed across groups. The \textbf {capability} group's baseline is an Initialized (deliberately randomised) parameter set, so the comparison measures whether PGOB regenerates a working simulator; the \textbf {deployment} group's baseline is the simulator's expert-calibrated shipped default, so the comparison measures whether PGOB still adds value on top of a well-tuned default. Because an Initialized-start and an expert-default improved-count answer different questions, they are reported side by side but never aggregated into a single number. Counts are per-observable improved fractions (PGOB closer to the real reference than the baseline)}{table.5}{}}
